# Bench baseline. Refresh whenever optimise/import internals change
# (rerun the exact commands below, replace numbers, note the machine).
# Regressions are judged against this file, not against memory.

machine: i5-14600KF (20 threads), ext4, linux 7.1.4-arch1-1
date: 2026-07-21

## bench/run.sh 400 2000 5000 1   (800k files, 194 MiB dedupable)

populate (addToStore)     7.039 s
optimise pass1 (cold)     7.881 s   linked 794600 files
optimise pass2 (warm)     0.013 s   linked 0

History: serial optimiseStore (pre thread-pool, same params, same
machine) cold pass was ~9-12 s; the parallel win on this box is
bounded by link-farm creation, not scanning. Commit 01ad51c holds the
original 1000x1000x100k serial capture: populate 14.1 s, cold 23.0 s.
Populate was 17.120 s until sourceToSink learned to buffer, and
9.277 s until the canonical restore killed the canonicalise walk (see
the syscall profile below); a NAR of many small files is nearly all
tokens and per-file metadata, so this shape gains most from both.

## build/bench-import <root> 20000 32 10000   (640 MiB tree, 43% dup)

import (capture off)     0.331 s
optimise (capture off)   0.521 s   linked 11366
import (capture on)      0.378 s   linked 11366
optimise (capture on)    0.179 s

Capture trades ~0.03 s at import (second hash thread) for ~3x faster
optimise (no content re-read); linked counts must match on/off, a
divergence means the captured hashes drifted (see
tests/import-hashes.cc).

## bench/run-real.sh   (arch-base: 582 MiB, 33k entries, NVMe ext4)

capture off/on (cold farm)  import 0.638 / 0.676 s
                            optimise 0.579 / 0.2 s   linked 9731
fresh install (import-dir)  wall 0.9 s
update, 1-file variant      wall 0.9 s   streamed dedup 545.4 MiB
package update (+400 MiB)   wall 1.1 s

First run after a build is noise: capture-on optimise measured 0.931 s
cold and 0.227 s on every run after. Take the second number.

The update phase is the on-box nixgen-update/commit hot path. Cost
per duplicate file is two journaled metadata writes (farm hardlink +
atomic rename); NVMe does ~10 us/op, USB-class flash ~1-2 ms/op, so
the same 33k-file generation that optimises in 0.3 s here takes tens
of seconds on a stick. That is media, not code: to measure a box,
run with the work dir on the target medium:
  bench/run-real.sh <tree> /path/on/that/medium

## COLD=1 bench/run-real.sh   (page cache evicted before each import)

fresh install    1.9 s   (warm 0.9)
update, all dups 1.7 s   (warm 0.9)
package update   2.4 s   (warm 1.1)

Cache temperature moves more than any code change in this file: ~2x
on NVMe, and the gap scales with the medium's random-read cost. This
is the realistic commit shape (the box commits hours after boot, not
seconds after building the tree); the default warm numbers isolate
code changes, COLD=1 approximates the user experience. fadvise only
evicts data pages (dentries/inodes need root), so true after-boot
cold is somewhat worse than COLD=1 measures. Streamed dedup still
avoids the writes when content matches; what cold adds is re-reading
the source and the store db/farm metadata.

