## syscall profile   (import-dir of arch-base, strace -c -f / perf stat)

Import is three-way overlapped: the coroutine spine (dumpPath reads +
NAR framing, restore writes) plus AsyncHashSink (whole-NAR digest) and
AsyncFileHasher (per-file digests, streaming dedup), each on its own
thread behind a 64-slot queue. Roughly half the CPU is kernel time, so
syscall counts are the thing to watch, not just wall clock.

                    original   buffered+filter   +canonical restore
futex                939,993      415,188            ~436,000
newfstatat           188,153      155,072             121,991
llistxattr            33,082       33,082                   1
chmod (path)          25,416       25,416               1,811
geteuid               33,085       33,085                   3
task-clock            2116 ms     ~1580 ms            ~1570 ms
wall                  1.31 s      ~1.02 s              0.97 s

sourceToSink was unbuffered while its mirror image sinkToSource has
always wrapped its side in a 32 KiB CoroBufferedSink, with a comment
saying why. dumpPath emits the NAR as tiny tokens ("(", "type",
"regular", length words, padding), so unbuffered each token resumed
the coroutine and became its own queue push into both hash threads: a
mutex, a notify and an allocation apiece. Upstream mostly uses the
buffered direction; import-dir uses the other one, on every commit.

Follow-ups tried, with verdicts (measure, then promote or discard):

- PROMOTED: the source-tree stat doubling was import-dir's noSpecials
  PathFilter: archive.cc called filter(path) (a raw ::lstat) and then
  immediately dump() -> accessor.lstat(path), while readDirectory had
  already returned every entry's type from d_type. dumpPath now skips
  fifo/socket entries itself and import-dir passes no filter: 188k ->
  155k newfstatat, one lstat per entry. Wall-neutral on NVMe (hot
  dentry cache); the win is code shape + sys time. Behavior pinned by
  tests/specials-skip.sh, since the old mechanism is gone.
- DISCARDED: memoising tryDedup's farm probes (hash -> size, worker
  thread owns the map). A/B on the warm all-dup import: 107,571 vs
  104,459 newfstatat, 3% for 17 lines. The 440x-probed .links entries
  in the profile belong to the optimise pass (one probe per file
  sharing that content), not tryDedup; optimise with capture is
  already 0.2 s and parallel, so not worth chasing either.
- DISCARDED: raising SourceToSink's BufferedSink from 32 KiB to
  256 KiB. ~5% wall, futex 425k -> 385k: a knob, not a fix, and the
  remaining futexes are AsyncFileHasher's per-file metadata events
  (~4 per file), not data chunks. Batching those events is the one
  real cut left on the futex side, if it is ever worth the churn.
  Re-swept after the canonical restore landed: 8K/32K/256K measure
  463k/446k/446k futex and identical wall, so above the 32 KiB
  default the curve is flat and the knob is settled, not just
  discarded. Alignment is a non-factor throughout: no O_DIRECT, and
  the hashers take unaligned input.

- PROMOTED: canonical restore (upstream's own FIXME at the old
  canonicalise call site: "merge into restorePath"). RestoreSink in
  canonical mode creates files 0444, stamps mtime 1 through the still
  open fd, fchmods exec files 0555 without the fstat, canonicalises
  each directory when its subtree completes, and symlink mtimes go
  through the parent fd. The post-restore canonicalisePathMetaData
  walk disappears: llistxattr 33k -> 1, geteuid 33k -> 3, path chmod
  25.4k -> 1.8k, newfstatat 155k -> 122k. On nixgen-commit's store
  disk that is one journaled metadata write less per restored file,
  which is where USB-class media pays 1-2 ms apiece. Two ordering
  traps, both hit and fixed: directory canonicalisation must wait for
  the streamed dedup (its link+rename fails against 0555 and bumps the
  fresh mtime), so capture-mode restores defer dirs until the hasher
  drains; and the restore root must stay writable until moveFile has
  renamed it out of the temp dir (cross-parent directory renames need
  write on the moved dir), so the sink never finishes the root and the
  final-path owner runs canonicaliseTimestampAndPermissions once.
  moveFile silently swallows non-EXDEV rename failures, which turned
  both traps into "path vanished" mysteries two calls later.
  Fallbacks stay on the old full walk: Flat restores, and a store dir
  carrying a default POSIX ACL (children would inherit xattrs the walk
  used to strip; one llistxattr on the store dir per import decides).
  Verified: store-path hashes byte-identical, all 58 unit TAP ok,
  arch meta-test PASS (savemeta/restmeta contract bit-identical),
  update-test FAST=1 full PASS (commit/update/remove/switch/setup in
  the box, three boots). Also retired bootstrap.sh's destructive
  find -delete of sockets/fifos (the dump skips them itself).

- DISCARDED: dropping loadInodeHash() from the per-path optimise (the
  farm scan reads the whole .links dir per import, which smelled like
  O(store) paid per commit). Measured on the warm all-dup import: the
  scan is ~100 batched getdents that lets readDirectoryIgnoringInodes
  drop already-linked files from the walk entirely; without it the
  walk pays 2 extra lstats per deduped file. 74,490 newfstatat with
  the scan vs 121,662 without: the shortcut wins until a farm of
  ~14M entries, which no box will see. The one scenario that could
  flip it (cold farm directory on USB-class flash vs cache-hot
  lstats) needs a real box to measure; on syscall count it loses
  everywhere.

- DISCARDED: -march=native (measured, not just reasoned). Three runs
  each: 1480-1496 ms task-clock native vs 1467-1502 generic, synth
  populate 0.886 vs 0.883 s. The hot loops never see compile flags:
  SHA-256 (libcrypto), BLAKE3 and glibc memcpy all dispatch SHA-NI/
  AVX2 by CPUID at runtime, half the time is kernel-side anyway, and
  native-built payload binaries would SIGILL on older boxes the ISO
  boots. If a CPU floor is ever wanted, -march=x86-64-v3 is the
  shippable form of the same idea; expect the same nothing.

Still open, measured: ~75k target-store stats remain (optimise walk +
farm probes); optimise with capture is 0.2 s and parallel, so the
remaining spend is known and cheap. The import side is done.
